What will not work <p>Processing both strings left to right and skipping <code>#</code> will obviously not work. Once we have \(i=1\) and \(j=1\):</p> \[ \begin{align} s &amp;= a\fbox{b}\#c \\  t &amp;= a\fbox{d}\#c \end{align} \] <p>our checks will fail too early.</p> <p>An obvious plan comes to mind where we process both strings in reverse instead.</p> <pre><code>fun backspaceCompare1(s: String, t: String): Boolean {
  var i = s.length - 1
  var j = t.length - 1
  while (i &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; j &gt;= 0) {
    if (s[i] == '#') {
      i -= 2
      continue
    }
    if (t[j] == '#') {
      j -= 2
      continue
    }
    if (s[i] != t[j]) return false
    i--
    j--
  }
  return i == -1 &amp;&amp; j == -1
}
</code></pre> <p>However, this fails for strings like <code>"a##c"</code>, as we jump from the rightmost <code>#</code> to <code>a</code> and end up not deleting it.</p> Expand <p>We compare not the strings themselves, but the "derived" string.</p> <pre><code>fun backspaceCompare(s: String, t: String): Boolean {
  return s.derivedString().compare(t.derivedString())
}
</code></pre> <p>Here "derived" string strips <code>#</code> and its left neighbour.</p> <pre><code>private fun String.derivedString(): java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt; {
  val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt;()
  for (c in this) {
    if (c != '#') stack.push(c)
    else {
      if (stack.isNotEmpty()) stack.pop() // (1)
    }
  }
  return stack
}
</code></pre> <ol> <li>repeated backspace in an empty text editor are allowed. we are just left with empty string.</li> </ol> <p>where <code>compare</code> is as follows:</p> <pre><code>private fun java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt;.compare(other: java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt;): Boolean {
  while (isNotEmpty() &amp;&amp; other.isNotEmpty()) {
    if (pop() != other.pop()) return false
  }
  return isEmpty() &amp;&amp; other.isEmpty()
}
</code></pre>

Expand <p>If you look at the provided examples, all we need to do is strip the outermost <code>()</code>. To do so, we essentially need to drop all parentheses at depth <code>0</code>. </p> <p>Let's start simple with the following boilerplate code. We process the string character by character, keeping track of the depth. Every time we encounter an opening parentheses, that's increasing <code>depth</code>, and every time we encounter a closing parentheses, that's a decreasing <code>depth</code>.</p> <pre><code>val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt;()
var depth = 0

for (c in s) {
  if (c == '(') {
    stack.push(c)
    depth++
  } else {
    stack.pop()
    depth--
  }
}
</code></pre> <p>From here, we introduce a string builder to collect the answer. We only populate it at \(\text{depth} \ge 1\).</p> <pre><code>fun removeOuterParentheses(s: String): String {
  val sb = StringBuilder()
  val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt;()
  var depth = 0

  for (c in s) {
    if (c == '(') {
      if (depth &gt; 0) sb.append(c)

      stack.push(c)
      depth++
    } else {
      stack.pop()
      depth--

      if (depth &gt; 0) sb.append(c)
    }
  }
  return sb.toString()
}
</code></pre> <p>Why is the <code>sb.append</code> placement not symmetrical? We can explain that by an example</p> Cursor position Illustration Evaluation of <code>depth</code> \(0\) <code>(())</code><code>^•••</code> <code>depth &gt; 0</code> check should happen first \(1\) <code>(())</code><code>•^••</code> <code>depth</code> is \(1\) so append it to <code>sb</code> \(2\) <code>(())</code><code>••^•</code> <code>depth &gt; 0</code> check should happen later \(3\) <code>(())</code><code>•••^</code> <code>depth</code> is \(0\) so don't append it to <code>sb</code>

