Expand <p>Starting from right to left, we use a monotonic stack on \((i, n)\). Pop elememnts as long as \(top &gt; n\). We'll be left with either an empty stack (no discount), or a \(top \le n\), which is out discount.</p> <pre><code>fun finalPrices(prices: IntArray): IntArray {
  val stack = ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()
  for ((i, p) in prices.withIndex().reversed()) {
    while (stack.isNotEmpty() &amp;&amp; stack.last() &gt; p) {
      stack.removeLast()
    }
    if (stack.isNotEmpty()) {
      prices[i] = p - stack.last()
    }
    stack.addLast(p)
  }
  return prices
}
</code></pre> <ul> <li>\(8, 4, 6, 2, \fbox{3}\) stack has nothing, so no discount.</li> <li>\(8, 4, 6, \fbox{2}, 3\) stack is \((3]\), and we pop it as long as \(top &gt; 2\). Nothing is left on stack, so no discount.</li> <li>\(8, 4, \fbox{6}, 2, 3\) stack is \((2]\), so our discount is \(2\), leading to \(6-2\) price.</li> <li>\(8, \fbox{4}, 6, 2, 3\) stack is \((6, 2]\). We pop \(6\) and end up with \(2\) discount.</li> <li>\(\fbox{8}, 4, 6, 2, 3\) stack is \((4, 2]\). We get a \(4\) discount.</li> </ul>

Expand <p>Obviously we can use a monotonic stack, but the issue is that this linked list implementation does not allow right-to-left traversal.</p> <p>To handle this, we reverse the list.</p> Reverse list and at the same time find its length<pre><code>private fun reverse(head: ListNode?): Pair&lt;ListNode?, Int&gt; {
  var size = 0
  var curr = head
  var prev: ListNode? = null
  while (curr != null) {
    val next = curr.next
    curr.next = prev

    prev = curr
    curr = next
    size++
  }
  return prev to size
}
</code></pre> <p>With this, monotonic stack can now be applied in a straighforward manner.</p> <pre><code>fun nextLargerNodes(head: ListNode?): IntArray {
  var (head, size) = reverse(head)
  val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()
  val answer = IntArray(size)

  var i = size - 1
  while (head != null) {
    while (stack.isNotEmpty() &amp;&amp; stack.peek() &lt;= head.`val`) {
      stack.pop()
    }
    answer[i--] = if (stack.isEmpty()) 0 else stack.peek()
    stack.push(head.`val`)
    head = head.next
  }
  return answer
}
</code></pre>

Expand <p>It is exactly like any other NGE problem, except this time we have to maintain the array since it's an ongoing algo.</p> <pre><code>class StockSpanner() {

  data class Pair(val day: Int, val price: Int) // 

  private var day = 0
  private val stack = ArrayDeque&lt;Pair&gt;()

  fun next(price: Int): Int {
    while (stack.isNotEmpty() &amp;&amp; stack.last().price &lt;= price) {
      stack.removeLast()
    }
    val span = if (stack.isEmpty()) day + 1 else day - stack.last().day
    stack.addLast(Pair(day++, price))
    return span
  }

}
</code></pre>

