Key Insight <p>The main hurdle here is finding the minimum element in each subarray. But we can flip this problem on it's head:</p> <p>Given a value \(v\) at index \(i\), we can find subarrays where \(v\) is the minimum element.</p> <p>To do so, we create two auxiliary arrays:</p> <ul> <li><code>left[i]</code>: The index of the Previous Less Element. This is the closest element to the left of \(i\) that is smaller than <code>arr[i]</code>.</li> <li><code>right[i]</code>: The index of the Next Less Element. This is the closest element to the right of \(i\) that is smaller than <code>arr[i]</code>.</li> </ul> <p>We can use the monotonic stack pattern to populate these two arrays. For a given index \(i\), we then know the contiguous subarray where \(a_i\) is the smallest element.</p> \[ a_{\text{left}[i] + 1}, \ a_{\text{left}[i] + 2}, \ \dots, \ a_i, \ \dots, \ a_{\text{right}[i] - 2}, \ a_{\text{right}[i] - 1} \] <p>Because the choice of where the subarray starts is completely independent of where it ends, we multiply the possibilities together (Combinatorics Product Rule). Total subarrays where arr[i] is thus</p> \[ (i - left[i]) \times (right[i] - i) \] <p>Note</p> <p>Given an array of length \(n\), the number of subarrays in it are \(\frac{n (n+1)}{2}\). However, if we apply the same logic here, many of those subarray won't even include index \(i\). Which is why we can't do the following:</p> \[ \begin{align} n &amp;= ((\text{right})[i] - 1) - ((\text{left})[i] + 1) + 1 \\ \text{count} &amp;= \frac{n(n+1)}{2} \end{align} \] Full Solution <pre><code>fun sumSubarrayMins(arr: IntArray): Int {
  val stack = ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()
  // index of element smaller than arr[i] in [0, i)
  val left = IntArray(arr.size)
  // index of element smaller than arr[i] in (i, n)
  val right = IntArray(arr.size)

  for ((i, n) in arr.withIndex()) {
    while (stack.isNotEmpty() &amp;&amp; arr[stack.last()] &gt;= n) { // (1)
      stack.removeLast()
    }
    left[i] = if (stack.isEmpty()) -1 else stack.last()
    stack.addLast(i)
  }

  stack.clear()

  for ((i, n) in arr.withIndex().reversed()) {
    while (stack.isNotEmpty() &amp;&amp; arr[stack.last()] &gt; n) { // (2)
      stack.removeLast()
    }
    right[i] = if (stack.isEmpty()) arr.size else stack.last()
    stack.addLast(i)
  }

  var sum = 0L
  for (i in arr.indices) {
    val count = (i - left[i]) * (right[i] - i)
    sum += count * arr[i]
  }
  return sum.toInt()
}
